<dl id="n05162b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05162b">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05162b"> 162(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> N, son of N, comes out / to be stoned <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n05162b"><li>FW 70.34 </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/lexc.htm#n05162b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/l39c.htm#n05162b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n05162b">MS BL 474722-249</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:242 <a name="cd5" href="../../FF/fdra/cda.htm#cd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/c/cd5.htm#n05162b">Draft: I.3&sect;1.5</a>/2.5/3.5</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Lightfoot, upon Matt. xxvii., 31, says: &ldquo;These things are delivered in Sanhedrim (cap. vi., hal. 4) of one that is guilty of stoning. If there be no defence found for him, they led him out to be stoned, and a crier went before, say aloud thus: &lsquo;<mark>N., the son of N., comes out to be stoned</mark>, because he hath done so and so. The witnesses against him are N. and N.; whosoever can bring anything in his defence, let him come forth and produce it.&rsquo; <small> G.W. Foote and J.M. Wheeler, eds., <a name="SEPH" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SEPH"><cite title="source">The Jewish Life of Christ</cite></a>, (1879) 40</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
